American Painting Section of the Mounted Photograph Collection

did.unittitle: American Painting Section of the Mounted Photograph Collection
did.abstract: Consists of reproductive photographs of original paintings from a variety of countries, cultures, time periods and in a variety of styles.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The photographs in the collection were acquired, over a sixty year period, from a diversearray of sources, including newspapers, magazines, auction catalogs, books, galleryannouncements, calendars, postcards, and as gifts or purchases.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Yale University is not the copyright holder of the images in the collection; therefore, thephotographs in the collection cannot be used for publication purposes, or for use within anyform of non-print media. Photocopying is permitted for research and study purposes only.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: The Photograph Collection of the Art and Architecture Library, Yale University.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Anyone can use the photograph collection for reference purposes, but only members of theYale University community can check out the photographs, on a temporary basis, for thepurpose of research and study for Yale University courses.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The photograph collection was begun in the 1930's, by the Yale University School of FineArts, for the purpose of teaching and study. Subsequently, in 1952, the photograph collectionbecame a part of the Art and Architecture Library where it progressively grew, and also,continued to be utilized as a reference, research, and instructional tool by faculty and students.At the present time, the photograph collection is primarily used as a resource of images forphoto study by students for History of Art and related courses, but the collection is also stillused, albeit on a less frequent level, for reference and research purposes. As a result of boththe proliferation of a collection of digitized images, and the need to economize space in thepending construction of a new Arts Library; in 1999, it was proposed that the photographcollection be relocated as an archival collection to the University's off-site Library ShelvingFacility, and that a finding aid be created to provide efficient access to the materials within thecollection.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The photograph collection consists of approximately 195,000 mounted black and white,and color, photographic reproductions of original works significant to the realms of the historyof art and the history of architecture. The collection embraces both Western and non-Westerncultures, and furthermore, encompasses time periods stretching from prehistoric times to thepresent. The collection is multidimensional in nature incorporating Architecture, Painting,Sculpture and the Minor Arts. Drawing is also represented within the collection. A large groupof folders containing miscellaneous clippings are dispersed throughout the collection, and theyaccompany related sections and photographs within the collection. Three different sizephotographs comprise the collection - small (which comprises the bulk of the collection),medium and large. Furthermore, the collection also includes a group of photographs referred toas white mounts, which are merely photographs of varied sizes mounted on white mat board.

Series II: Painting consists of reproductive photographs of original paintings from a varietyof countries, cultures, time periods and in a variety of styles. Photographs of drawings are alsoincluded, and are interfiled with those of paintings; however, if there were a large quantity ofdrawings for a particular artist, a separate section was made in that artist's hierarchy fordrawings. Folders containing miscellaneous clippings are filed with related sections in thecollection.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Painting is arranged alphabetically by country, and alphabetically by artist therein. desctiption fo all four sectionsSeries I: Architecture

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The sub-series, United States, is divided into two major sections: Anonymous and Miscellaneous & Individual Artists.
The Anonymous section is arranged chronologicallyl by century, and by genre therein. The20th Century Anonymous subseries is divided into a general section, and then a genre section.

The Miscellaneous & Individual Artists section is arrangedalphabetically. Within each letter of the alphabet there is a Miscellaneous Artists section,followed by an Individual Artists section. The Miscellaneous Artists sections are divided intoalphabetic ranges. The Individual Artists sections are arranged alphabetically by artist. Withineach artist's division the arrangement is usually by location or chronology, but occasionally by genre if the artist was prolific. Photographs of drawings by artists are interfiled with their paintings, unless there are a substantial amount of drawings, in which case a separate section is incorporated within that particular artist'shierarchy.
